node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dwell on August 23, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
“I rented a sander from Home Depot,” says interior designer Alex Fawcett (@alcfawcett), who spent two weeks refinishing the floors of his midcentury home in Connecticut. Alex bought the 1956 home directly from the architect’s family, which came with a caveat: Since the residence is the only one designed and built by their father, commercial architect Cyril K. Smith, the new resident had to promise to uphold the home’s innate design sense. As a fan of classic design, that wouldn’t be an issue for Alex and his DIY approach. “I really wanted to create something that made it feel authentic, but that didn’t feel like it was new,” he says. A hands-on remodel—hence the sander rental—would ensue, complete with structural mishaps, the expansion of tight spaces, and an all-black kitchen that the home itself demanded. “I have to spend time with the space and take it all in,” says Alex. “It tells me what it wants.” Swipe through to see the before photos, and take the full tour when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.
–

In Argentina, the crowning glory of this single-level home is truly what sits above it. Local architect @fabripugliese.arq designed a barrel-vaulted brick roof that appears to hover inches above the residence. Through extensive glazing, Casa Monopoli yields a strong indoor/outdoor connection in almost every room. The dwelling articulates what Pugliese refers to as “two systems: a handcrafted one and an industrialized one.” The handcrafted system refers to the home’s undulating roofline while the industrialized system includes “a structural, metal grid that allows the organization of the layout.” Supported by the metal-beam system, the roof extends to shade exterior gathering spaces. Inside, the home is divided into two areas—public and private—separated by a central patio. “This gap allows indirect light to enter throughout,” says Pugliese. The abundance of natural light that sweeps inside the structure reflects off the brickwork and infuses the minimalist interiors with a warm, reddish hue. Wooden accents further enhance the home’s neutral material palette, while polished concrete floors lend a contemporary flair. Take the full tour of Casa Monopoli at the link in bio.

Sometimes it helps to have a history. For the renovation of an outdated home in Austin, Texas, one of the owners, Sarah Mitchell, called upon long-time family friend and architect Arthur Furman (@furtex). "We went to high school together, and our families have had an architectural connection since the 1990s," says Furman, who goes on to mention that his dad designed Sarah’s aunt and uncle’s home on Lake Austin. Sarah and her husband, Ernesto Humpierres, were hoping to update their residence to accommodate their growing family, but also to better connect it to the natural surroundings of the historic Clarksville neighborhood in which it stands. "It was a two-bedroom, two bathroom house with a tiny kitchen and poor access to the beautiful backyard," says Furman, cofounder of @sideangleside.co with his wife, architect Annie-Laurie Grabiel (@annie_laurie__). "The entire floor plan was awkward and inefficient, but the biggest complaint was the lack of natural light and views of the jaw-dropping live oak trees." Along with prioritizing the surroundings, maintaining a light carbon footprint was important to the couple—they operate @neutrall_life, a carbon-neutral upcycled glassware company—so they asked for a green roof and recycled denim insulation, and that construction be approached as sustainably as possible. "The pallet was tonal and textural, with minimally treated wood, plaster walls and ceilings, and weathered metals in earthy tones," Furman says. "The goal was always to let the materials be themselves, allowing the house to become a part of the vegetation rather than a competitor." To take a walk through the renovated Clarksville House, hit the link in bio and try Dwell+.

This 4,036-square-foot vacation home—shared by a group of four friends—is a true tribute to the land. In Portugal’s Grândola, a small town in the southern Alentejo region, local studio @bakgordonarquitectos designed the house with what the team refers to as two “fresco” rooms that bookend the geometric structure on the east and west ends. The east end includes an indoor/outdoor dining area with a traditional wood-burning stove. On the west, a cozy seating area positions itself for the perfect sunset. A long, open-plan living and dining space stretches between the two areas, and connects to a pool that runs alongside the home’s south-facing exterior. Part of the rear partition is clad in Alentejo marble slabs, which the architects chose both to protect the pool wall and also to serve as an ornamental element inspired by irrigation tanks in the region. In the center of the home, a small open-air patio is surrounded by three suites, each of which has an interior terrace and en suite bathroom. To further connect the home with its location, the architects covered the interior and exterior spaces with pigmented lime mortar, a common material used for construction in the area. The designers also enlisted a cork covering for the entirety of the home—another regionally-popular material—which “makes the house breathe” and acts as a thermal insulator, say the architects. Take a look through the jaw-dropping Casa Azul at the link in bio.

node.text:
In Barcelona, the bajos—or ground floor—of an apartment building has always had a bad rap. Lack of natural light and dampness are issues, but the opportunity to have a garden in the busy city is enticing. @scala_studio, a young interior design firm founded by Anna Raventós and Lea Viscasillas, was given the opportunity to transform an abandoned office building’s bajos into a father and daughter’s home in Barcelona’s St. Gervasi district. "A haven of peace in the midst of the city’s bustle," is how the designers describe the result. The owner of the space has strong connections to the island of Ibiza and the Costa Brava, and wished to translate a northern Mediterranean feel to the decor where light meets natural warmth and informality. To accommodate this, the designers restored the original woodwork and moldings—such as the arches that lead to the rear garden, and the fireplace. These period details acted as a driver of the original design and decor scheme, which was governed by selecting pieces with a certain romanticism and story to tell. Even the flooring, which was sourced from a 1960s Croatian sawmill, is living a second life in the renovated home. Another impressive feat in reuse comes in the form of a two bedroom unit in the former shed out back. Inside the detached structure, two bedrooms sit on either side of the main bathroom with a walk-in shower. Polished concrete floors and natural wood create a neutral yet cozy ambiance in the shade of a giant ash tree. Viscasillas reflects on the choice: "For us, the luxury was creating the external bedrooms. That’s an opportunity that doesn’t arise every day." Take the full tour of the Muntaner Residence when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

node.text:
Behind a dense wall of Passionfruit vines stand twin houses just outside Brisbane, Australia. To mediate the noise and dust from a nearby road, architect John Ellway (@jellway) applied a mesh facade to the dwellings, now covered after only six months. Because the homes are situated on a slope, steel stilts raise the living areas above road level, creating an undercroft surrounded by lush planting. Despite the conscious decisions made to distance the homes from pollutants, Ellway intended for the homes to cultivate community with their surroundings. “In a lot of suburban housing, people drive into a garage, shut the automatic door, and never step outside their sealed box,” he says. “Not in these houses. The entry path is elongated from the footpath to almost halfway up the block, entering a courtyard in the center of the house. It makes a smaller parcel of land feel bigger, but also gives opportunity for casual interactions with the neighbors and provides passive surveillance over each other’s property.” In fact, nearly the entire design focuses on the idea of shared space, not only with the residents of the adjoining house, but also within: The more public spaces in the homes—living, dining, and courtyard—were prioritized in terms of size and detailing, while the bedrooms have a much smaller footprint. This encourages family members to spend time together in the common areas. Designing two homes with community in mind is also a very successful business strategy, allowing for reduced deliveries, use of prefabricated framing, and simple materials such as fiber cement, plasterboard, and aluminum framed windows. In the end, the two lushly landscaped homes came in at around $2,250 AUD per square meter ($153 USD per square foot). Take the full tour of the lush Twin Houses at the link in bio.
–

On a steep escarpment in Los Angeles, an architect got to build his version of the quintessentially L.A. home. “Many of Los Angeles’ iconic modern houses float above the city like tethered spaceships on stilts,” says @clivewilkinson. “I had always yearned for the opportunity to design my own floating house.” Wilkinson organized the 3,700-square-foot house around a staircase accessed directly from the entry. As soon as you swing open the large pivot door that serves as the front gate, you’re hit with the view, and upstairs, the open living, dining, and kitchen area is oriented toward it. But in the comparatively compact family room and bedrooms, the house manages to revel in the simplicity and domesticity of nearby flatland residences—think bungalows and Spanish-Colonial revival homes—that are standard fare for the region. “I put a lot into this,” says Clive. What he’s gotten out has already proven a hit, as much with family and friends as with its creator. Take a look through the awe-inspiring Wilkinson Residence at the link in bio.

Facing a steep site, poor ground quality, and strong, year-round winds, Pablo Dikenstein of @estudiodikenstein_arquitectos had quite the challenge when designing a beach home in Matanzas, Chile, 300 feet above sea level. The space “provides an astonishing view of the Pacific Ocean,” he says. “Amid the hostile yet charming setting, the structure simultaneously calls upon us to connect and reflect on the best way to inhabit this coastal area.” To temper battering gales and camouflage the home in the landscape, the architect crafted a wooden, honeycomb-like facade that appears suspended in air above exposed concrete retaining walls. A 131-foot-long red ribbon connects the two levels and flows down the hillside, an addition that “allows both structures to benefit from a sea view, and creates a visually pleasing break,” explains Dikenstein. “Casa Panal offers a radical experience and an experimental way of living as it integrates all spaces, both outside and inside, vertical and horizontal.” Take a walk through the entire residence at the link in bio.

For the first time ever, Italian futurist Giacomo Balla’s former apartment in Rome will be open for public viewing. The exhibition, hosted by the city’s National Museum of 21st Century Art (@museomaxxi), grants visitors access to the artist’s otherwise upper-middle class flat that he, his wife, and his two daughters began transforming in 1929 as an inhabitable canvas of art—painting the walls, designing and building furniture, and creating their own imaginative floor tiles, carpets, upholstery, light fixtures, and dishes. The approach to domestication was odd, to be sure, but Balla walked the walk: His 1915 manifesto, penned in partnership with fellow countryman and painter Fortunado Depero, introduced the concept that living life itself should be a “total work of art.” For more on Casa Balla and the exhibition that celebrates the 150th anniversary of the artist's birth, head to the link in bio.

For a young family of five—with a new poodle puppy in tow—this revamped timber cottage in Sydney celebrates lively design. “It’s a humble home with little tweaks that make for playfulness,” says Rebekah Clayton, co-principal of local architecture firm @claytonorszaczky. The goal of the reno was to embrace all that made the weatherboard house special while maxing out the floor plan to better suit the family. To start, the interior walls were blown out to make way for an open-plan kitchen and living area, as well as three bedrooms, bathrooms, and a study. The architects also constructed a cantilevered rear addition that sits atop the original structure—with an eye-catching twist. “For each of our projects, we like to have a gizmo—something fun that’s a bit unexpected or that makes the [structure] unique,” explains Clayton. The showstopper in this case is the fixed screen that wraps the building with white aluminum slats, offering high-visual but low-maintenance impact. Behind the screen, oversize glass doors open up to let in fresh breezes without sacrificing shade or privacy. Despite its striking addition and renovation, the Workers House blends in seamlessly with the rest of the neighborhood from the street. Clayton sums it up: “In some ways this house is the opposite of a standout, and that’s what we consider to be its greatest success.” Take a look through the renovated Workers House at the link in bio.

Dubbed the Michigan Loft for its coveted spot overlooking Michigan Avenue in Chicago’s Motor Row district, this transformed space occupies a century-old building initially used for automotive assembly. Before, its 2,250 square feet felt crowded and disjointed—and altogether too raw. Now, a wood platform wraps the living spaces, creating a more intimate scale. "As one enters this dwelling through a low, wood-clad transition zone, the overwhelming feeling of being inside a large industrial room is very much subdued," says architect @vladimir_radutny. Variations in level allow visitors to experience changing vantage points while moving through more defined areas, from the lofted studio space to the kitchen below. The materials used—like black metal and wood—also create a more cohesive home while maintaining the building’s character. Las Tres Marias—a shared holiday home for three sisters in Spain’s Mont-Roig del Camp—is a striking renovation of a 1960s dwelling that embodies the “courtyard house” character of coastal homes along the Mediterranean. Working in collaboration, architects @bajetgirame and @nicolasburckhardtarchitekten relied on a preexisting wall that lined the property to connect the home to expansive patios. “We sought to create a retreat that is a deliberately ambiguous habitat between the inside and out,” say the architects. While the former layout comprised small, detached spaces, the redesigned 1,292-square-foot residence features living, dining, kitchen, and loggia areas that flow freely under both new and old arches.
